  "questionId": "gfg-sub-aptitude-3d-shapes-names-definitions-properties-formulas-and-real-life-examples",
  "title": "3D Shapes",
  "content": {
    "problemStatement": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>3D shapes are solid figures that have three dimensions \u2014 length, width, and height. Unlike flat 2D shapes, they have depth and occupy space. Because they take up space, they have volume.</span></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"3dshapes\" height=\"400\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes.webp\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes.webp 800w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes-200.webp 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes-300.webp 300w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes-660.webp 660w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250227125528852134/3dshapes-768.webp 768w\" width=\"800\"/><figcaption>3D Shapes</figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"parts-of-3d-shapes\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Parts of 3D Shapes</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Faces:</strong></b><span> The flat or curved surfaces of a three-dimensional shape.</span><br/><b><strong>Edges:</strong></b><span> The line segments where two faces meet.</span><br/><b><strong>Vertices:</strong></b><span> The corner points where two or more edges meet.</span></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"d\" height=\"567\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d.webp\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d.webp 800w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d-200.webp 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d-300.webp 300w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d-660.webp 660w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260218173811277626/d-768.webp 768w\" width=\"800\"/><figcaption> </figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"basic-properties-of-3d-shapes\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Basic Properties of 3D Shapes</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Three-dimensional (3D) shapes have special properties that make them different from 2D shapes.</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>Surface Area:</strong></b><span> The total area covered by all the outer surfaces of a 3D shape.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><b><strong>Volume:</strong></b><span> The space occupied by a 3D shape. It is measured in cubic units.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>Dimensions:</strong></b><span> Every 3D shape is defined by three dimensions: length, width, and height, which determine its overall size and form.</span></li></ul><h2 id=\"3d-shapes-around-us\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>3D Shapes Around Us</span></h2><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"3D-Shapes-around-Us\" height=\"745\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us.webp\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us.webp 1042w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us-200.webp 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us-300.webp 300w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us-660.webp 660w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us-768.webp 768w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260217180719017025/3D-Shapes-around-Us-1024.webp 1024w\" width=\"1042\"/><figcaption> </figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"3d-shapes-names-geometry-property-applications\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>3D Shapes Names</span></h2><h3 id=\"cube\" style=\"text-align:left\"><b><strong>Cube</strong></b></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/cube/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Cube</span></a><span> is a solid shape or three-dimensional shape that has 6 square faces, 12 edges, and 8 Vertices.</span></p><img alt=\"Shapes-11\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250228095948123013/Shapes-11.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"cuboid\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Cuboid</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/cuboid-shape-and-properties/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>cuboid</span></a><span>, also known as a rectangular prism, where the faces are rectangular. All the angle measures 90 degrees.</span></p><img alt=\"Shapes-12\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250228100122980347/Shapes-12.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"cone\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Cone</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/cone/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Cone</span></a><span> is a three-dimensional object or a solid that has a circular base that tapers easily to a single point and has a single vertex. </span></p><img alt=\"Shapes-16\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250228100229386968/Shapes-16.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"cylinder\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Cylinder</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>The </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/cylinder/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Cylinder</span></a><span> is a three-dimensional shape that has two circular bases connected by a curved surface.</span></p><img alt=\"Shapes-15\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250228100322000358/Shapes-15.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"sphere\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Sphere</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>The </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/sphere/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Sphere</span></a><span> is a three-dimensional shape where every point on its surface is equidistant from its center. It has no edges, vertices, or flat shapes.</span></p><img alt=\"Shapes-13\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250228100422965318/Shapes-13.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"hemisphere\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Hemisphere</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/sphere/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Hemisphere</span></a><span> is a 3D Shape that represents half of a sphere. </span></p><img alt=\"Shapes-14\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250228102742870824/Shapes-14.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"square-pyramid\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Square Pyramid</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/square-pyramid-formula/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>square pyramid</span></a><span> is three dimensional geometric shape with a square base and triangular faces that meet at a single point called the apex.</span></p><img alt=\"square-pyramid\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250320162527263929/square-pyramid-300.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"hexagonal-pyramid\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Hexagonal Pyramid</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/hexagonal-pyramid-formula/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>hexagonal pyramid</span></a><span> is a three-dimensional geometric shape with a hexagonal base and has 6 triangular faces.</span></p><img alt=\"hexagonal-pyramid\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250320162832412493/hexagonal-pyramid-300.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"triangular-prism\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Triangular Prism</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/triangular-prism/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Triangular Prism</span></a><span> is a three-dimensional geometric shape with two identical triangular bases connected by three rectangular faces.</span></p><img alt=\"image\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250304230207505295/image-300.png\" width=\"inherit\"/><h3 id=\"hexagonal-prism\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Hexagonal Prism</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/hexagonal-prism/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>hexagonal prism</span></a><span> is a three-dimensional geometric shape with two hexagonal bases connected by six rectangular faces.</span></p><img alt=\"hexagonal-prism\" height=\"inherit\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250304230341392936/hexagonal-prism-300.webp\" width=\"inherit\"/><h2 id=\"other-3d-shapes\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Other 3D Shapes</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A\u00a0</span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/polyhedrons/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>polyhedron</span></a><span>\u00a0is a 3D solid made up of flat polygonal faces, with edges meeting at vertices. Each face is a polygon, and the edges connect the faces at their vertices.</span></p><table><thead><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Name </span></p></th><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Faces</span></p></th><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Vertices</span></p></th><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Edges</span></p></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Tetrahedron</strong></b></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>4 faces</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>4 vertices</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>6 edges</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Octahedron</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>8 faces</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>6 vertices</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>12 edges</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Dodecahedron</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>12 faces</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>20 vertices</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>30 edges</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Icosahedron</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>20 faces</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>12 vertices</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>30 edges</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id=\"3d-shape-formulas\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>3D Shapes formulas </span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Here is the list of formulas for 3D shapes, including surface area and volume:</span></p><table><thead><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>3D shape</span></p></th><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Surface Area</span></p></th><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Volume</span></p></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Cube</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>6a</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>a</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Cuboid</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>2(lb + bh + hl)</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>2h(l + b)</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Cone</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>\u03c0r(r + l) ( here l is slant height )</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>1/3\u03c0r</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Cylinder</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>2\u03c0r(r + h)</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>h</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Sphere</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>4\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>4/3\u03c0r</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Hemisphere</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>3\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>2/3\u03c0r</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Square Pyramid</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>s</span><sup><span>2 </span></sup><span>+ 2sl ( here s is the base area ) </span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>1/3s</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>h</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Hexagonal Prism</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>6sh + 3\u221a3s</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>[(3\u221a3)/2]s</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>h </span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Triangular Prism</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>(b x h) + (s</span><sub><span>1 </span></sub><span>+ s</span><sub><span>2</span></sub><span> + s</span><sub><span>3</span></sub><span>)</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>1/2(bhl)</span></p></td></tr><tr><th><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Hexagonal Pyramid</span></p></th><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>3ab + 3bs</span></p></td><td><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>abh</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table><h3 id=\"related-articles\" style=\"text-align:left\"><b><strong>Related Articles</strong></b></h3><blockquote><ul><li value=\"1\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/volume-formulas/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Volume Formula For 3D Shapes</span></a></li><li value=\"2\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/surface-area-formulas/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Surface Area Formula For 3D Shapes</span></a></li><li value=\"3\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/real-life-application-of-3d-shape/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Real Life Application of 3D Shapes</span></a></li></ul></blockquote>",
    "sampleTestCases": []
  }
}